%META:TOPICPARENT{name="WebHome"}%
---+ Overview

%TOC%

CGV Web is a zero-install, browser-native event display for the ATLAS
calorimeter system. It loads the real detector geometry exported from the
ATLAS GeoModel database, and draws on top of it the quantities that shifters
and analysers care about during a run: energy deposits per cell,
topological clusters, reconstructed tracks and the associated kinematic
summary.

The viewer runs entirely in WebGL2 via [[https://threejs.org/][Three.js]].
Cell identifiers are decoded by a Rust-compiled-to-WebAssembly module, so
mapping a 32-bit =caloId= to =(subDet, side, sampling, η-bin, φ-bin)= costs
a few microseconds and never blocks the main thread.

---++ What it renders

   * Tile Calorimeter — long barrel (LB) and the two extended barrels (EB±).
   * LAr EM — barrel (EMB) and end-caps (EMEC±).
   * HEC — four-wheel hadronic end-cap.
   * FCAL — three forward modules (FCAL1, FCAL2, FCAL3).
   * ATLAS Ghost — nine inactive-material envelopes for spatial context.
   * Reconstructed tracks and topological clusters from the current event.

---++ Colour convention

The colour palette is consistent across the scene, the panel headers and
the threshold sliders. Keep it in mind when reading a capture:

| *Sub-detector / object* | *Accent* | *Hex*    |
| TileCal                 | orange   | =#c87c18= |
| LAr EM                  | green    | =#27b568= |
| HEC                     | cyan     | =#66e0f6= |
| FCAL                    | copper   | =#b87333= |
| Tracks                  | yellow   | =#ffea00= |
| Clusters                | red      | =#ff4400= |

Active cells use a per-sub-detector gradient between cold (low E) and hot
(high E). Track lines are thin and solid; cluster outlines are dashed.

---++ Typical shifter workflow

   1. Open CGV Web in the Control Room browser.
   1. [[DataModes][Live mode]] auto-connects to the ATLAS Live feed via ATLANTIS; events arrive every few seconds.
   1. Drag, scroll and right-drag the canvas to orbit, zoom and pan around the detector.
   1. Use the right-hand [[EnergyThresholds][threshold panel]] to cut on TILE, LAr, HEC, FCAL, track p_T or cluster E_T.
   1. Click a cell to read its compact ATLAS-ID, η, φ and energy in the cell tooltip.
   1. Press =P= to save a screenshot at up to 10K resolution for logbook entries.

---++ Offline analysis

The same page accepts local JiveXML files (folder picker or drag-and-drop)
and bundled sample events. Multi-event XML is supported with a carousel
that auto-advances between files — useful during a shift debrief or for
building a quick training deck from a list of flagged events.

